The sixth method uses “analog ERFs,” that is to say, ERFs derived for locations with temperatures similar to those projected to occur in the future in the location of interest. Although the method has been criticized (
 Kinney et al. 2008), and although it assumes that the underlying confounding factors that contribute to the ERF can be transferred to a different location, it is popular (
 Hayhoe et al. 2004; 
 Knowlton et al. 2007; 
 Mills et al. 2014) because it draws upon epidemiological evidence that populations in warmer/colder regions tend to be less/more sensitive to relatively higher temperatures (
 Davis et al. 2003).
